Learning objectives

By the end of this lab session, the students should be able to

  1. Appreciate the importance of defining good features.
  2. Define features for text.
  3. Perform feature engineering on a real (text) data.

Feature Engineering

Feature engineering is the art of defining good features. Here we define a feature as a measurable characteristic of objects that are under consideration. For example, height (measured in meters) and age (measured in years) are features of people. In machine learning, feature engineering is part of data preprocessing. In machine learning we never work with real objects, we only deal with features defined for those objects, hence the success of a machine learning project often depends on the quality of the features. A good set of features do not only tell us what an object is but also what it is not (see Figure 2).

Figure 1. Cat and some cat features

Outside computer science or machine learning, feature is synonymous with variable.

Figure 2. Features on cats and dogs

The usefulness of feature engineering becomes more apparent when the raw data is not in numerical format and when we need to define higher level features. Some machine learning algorithms incorporate feature transformation to obtain higher level features and often they result in good performance. However, there is always a room for creativity and as Domingos put it “there is no replacement for the smarts you put into feature engineering”

Features that can be used for some data

Data Feature
images pixels, contours, textures
signal samples, spectograms
time series ticks, trends, reversals
biological dna, marker sequences, genes
text words, grammatical classes and relations

Advice on feature engineering

  1. Use domain knowledge to construct a better set of “ad hoc” features.
  2. Try different and as many features (as your resources will allow) and apply feature reduction techniques.
  3. Apply normalization.
  4. Subsample data.

Points to remember

  1. Redundant features help each other except in the case when they are perfectly correlated.
  2. Two features that are useless by themselves can be useful together (e.g. XOR problem ).

Tutorial on extracting features from text

This part of the tutorial will illustrate how to generate numerical features from text. The tutorial here is for the large part based from the paper of Kobayashi et al. (2017).

Our text are job advertisements posted online and our goal is to extract features that may be useful for job classification and/or automatic job information extraction from job descriptions.

Getting to know the data

The data file contain 150 English vacancies. Each file is a vacancy. You can download the data in Blackboard.

Import data

We are going to use the tm library for our text processing. Since we have separate files for each vacancy it is convenient to store them in a folder in your computer and use the DirSource function to read the files in R. If the text are in a table , use the VectorSource or `DataframeSource function. You can also specify a URI or XML source. To see the list of possible input locations invoke the following command

library(tm)
getSources()
## [1] "DataframeSource" "DirSource"       "URISource"       "VectorSource"   
## [5] "XMLSource"       "ZipSource"

Once we have specified the input location (in our case the directory source), we create a corpus of documents. In the language of text mining, a corpus is a collection of documents. This is done using the VCorpus function. By the way, in specifying the input location make sure to provide the correct path.

job_adverts <- VCorpus(DirSource("vladi"))

Document Cleaning

For this tutorial we are going to use words as features, hence our goal is to extract the words also called word tokenization. However, prior to that we want to clean the data by apply standard text preprocessing procedures such as lowercase transformation and extra whitespace removal. We can easily do this using the tm_map function.

job_adverts <- tm_map(job_adverts, content_transformer(tolower))
job_adverts <- tm_map(job_adverts, stripWhitespace)

See the effect of the preprocessing for the first document.

job_adverts[[1]]$content

Aside from the preprocessing procedures we applied above other common preprocessing procedures include punctuation removal and number removal.

Feature Engineering

One way to construct features is to build the so-called document-term matrix wherein the rows are the documents, the columns are the words (or tokens), and the entries are the raw frequencies of the words in each document. The dimensions of the matrix is equal to the number of documents by the number of unique tokens. This matrix is necessarily sparse since most words only appear in few documents.

Let us construct this using the DocumentTermMatrix function. Note that we decided to remove the punctuation and the numbers.

dtm <- DocumentTermMatrix(job_adverts, 
                          control = list(
                            removePunctuation=TRUE,
                            removeNumbers=TRUE
                            )
                          )

What is the dimensionality of the resulting document-by-term matrix?

Of course we can also define features aside from words. We can define bi-grams (consecutive words) and grammar based features. In this tutorial we focus on word features. Note that the document-by-term matrix is stored as a sparse matrix.

From the document-by-term matrix we can investigate some statistics such as the highest and lowest frequencies.

library(slam)
summary(col_sums(dtm))
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##    1.000    1.000    2.000    6.365    4.000 2119.000

Let us identify the top ten most frequent words

sort(col_sums(dtm), decreasing=TRUE)[1:10]
##        and        the       with experience        for     skills 
##       2119        797        514        440        381        253 
##   customer    ability management   business 
##        192        187        182        170

We can also use the findFreqTerms to find the most frequent terms. Below is the code to find the terms with a frequency of at least 100.

findFreqTerms(dtm, lowfreq=100)
##  [1] "ability"    "all"        "and"        "business"   "customer"  
##  [6] "customers"  "experience" "for"        "management" "project"   
## [11] "sales"      "skills"     "team"       "that"       "the"       
## [16] "with"       "work"       "years"

Aside from finding the frequent terms we can also identify which terms correlate with a given term.

findAssocs(dtm, terms = "verbal", corlimit = 0.3)
## $verbal
##      written       highly        drive      driving presentation 
##         0.58         0.46         0.35         0.32         0.32 
##    excellent        solid 
##         0.30         0.30

Notice that some of the most frequent words are prepositions. In terms of semantic contribution, they do not contribute to the meaning that much so better remove them, these words are also called stopwords.

dtm_new <- dtm[,!(Terms(dtm) %in% findFreqTerms(dtm, lowfreq = 100))]

# make sure that we also remove empty docs
dtm_new<-dtm_new[row_sums(dtm_new)>0,]

The new top frequent terms are

findFreqTerms(dtm_new, lowfreq = 60)
##  [1] "analysis"      "are"           "communication" "data"         
##  [5] "degree"        "design"        "develop"       "development"  
##  [9] "ensure"        "including"     "knowledge"     "maintain"     
## [13] "manage"        "must"          "new"           "other"        
## [17] "our"           "plans"         "process"       "products"     
## [21] "projects"      "provide"       "required"      "services"     
## [25] "store"         "strong"        "support"       "systems"      
## [29] "technical"     "use"           "working"       "your"

But wait there are still propositions. Let us use another technique to remove terms with low semantic contribution. Introducing… the idf or inverse document frequency. The idf is computed as \[idf(t,D)=\frac{N}{|\{d \in D : t \in d\}|}\] where \(N\) is the size of the corpus and the denominator is the number of documents where the term \(t\) appears. Terms not appearing in the corpus have an idf of \(\log N\). The idf measures the specifity of a term. Specificity measures the rareness or commonness of a term. Terms that are common have low idf. The idea of specificity is useful when doing text classification since highly common terms have low discrimination power. For example, in job classification using vacancies the terms “skills” and “experience” may not be good features since we would expect that most job advertisements mention these terms.

The idf is often multiplied to the term frequency to come up with a measure of importace of a term in a document considering the entire corpus. This measure is populary known as the tf-idf measure. \[tfidf(t,d,D)=tf(t,d) \cdot idf(t,D)\]

The tf-idf can be used for term filtering to remove unimportant terms.

Let us use tf-idf to further remove terms that are less important. Here we set the threshold slightly higher than the median. Can you guess the reason for selecting this threshold?

term_tfidf<-tapply(dtm_new$v/row_sums(dtm_new)[dtm_new$i], dtm_new$j, mean) * log2(nDocs(dtm_new)/col_sums(dtm_new>0))
summary(term_tfidf)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## 0.009263 0.029505 0.041785 0.052479 0.059253 0.850449
dtm_new<-dtm_new[,term_tfidf>=0.042]
dtm_new<-dtm_new[row_sums(dtm_new)>0,]
summary(col_sums(dtm_new))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.000   1.000   1.000   2.604   2.000  87.000
dim(dtm_new)
## [1]  150 2001

Our document-by-term matrix can be converted to a dense matrix using the as.matrix function and can be used as input to supervised and unsupervised machine learning techniques.

Summary

The feature engineering presented here is based on constructing the document by term matrix and is based on bag-of-words model which assumes that a document is a collection words (ignoring word order information), of course there are other approaches such as using one-hot encoding (more about this during the session on neural network). Furthermore, we can also apply other preprocessing and filtering techniques depending on the objectives (and often on the judgment of the researcher) of the project.

As further reading on feature engineering techniques for other raw data types. I encourage you to do a simple search on google scholar with the following keywords : “feature extraction data_type>” where “data_type” is either image, signal or time series.
